64. 4. imagInes remanere. According to Epicurus there iiow from objects not only images of coarser consistency which are perceived by the eye, but also those of more subtle nature which are directly perceived by the mind. Lucret.lV, 726ff. Such images continue to exist, even when the objects from which they proceed have passed away; which accounts for the presence in the mind of the forms of those long dead, as for exam· ple in dreams. Lucret. V, 63. Remanere is tobe understood of continu· ance in time, not in place; for, as Lucret. 1v, 728 says, simulacra vagan- tur. . . iu cunctas undique partis. Comp. Cic. De Div. II, 67, 137. For this reason the reading of the majority of Mss, pervenerint, would seem preferable to pervenerim, which hasbeen adopted by recent editors from four Mss. Comp. Jahrb. stir Phil. 1875, p. 691.
